liveStorefrontProfile.aboutUs:
At Morentz (est. 2007), we aim to add value to every single piece in our collection. We are a gallery, a workshop and an upholstery studio in one. Our team consists of about forty restorators, upholsterers, interior advisors and art historians. We are therefore able to provide our customer with every possible service. 

Every day, securely selected twentieth century design arrives at our warehouse from every corner of the world. We investigate every single edge and every inch of patina. We check the structure and condition thoroughly. This is where we add our value: what does a piece need? It might be a careful and complete restoration or a completely new upholstery, depending on each individual piece and each individual client. Our aim is to stay true to the original intention of the designer and at the same time fulfill the wishes of its new owner. At Morentz, nothing is impossible, because we love and care about our pieces as much as you do.

item.description:
Saporiti, four-seat sofa with two lounge Chairs, green velvet and rosewood, Italy 1960's. 

The sofa and chairs are designe order to give it that very distinguished long and low look. Loose cushions on seating and back. The tufted cushions give the long and straight design a bit more tension, yet the sofa keeps its powerful appearance. The rosewood frame is additionally reinforced by the double connections. In this the grain of the rosewood is beautifully visible.

We advise reupholstery as the original fabric shows signs of age and use, as well as the stuffing of the cushions. Please ask for more information about the options that our upholstery studio can offer you.

result.title: Saporiti Living Room Set in Original Velvet
result.description:
Saporiti, four-seat sofa with two lounge Chairs, green velvet and rosewood, Italy 1960's. 

The sofa and chairs are designe order to give it that very distinguished long and low look. Loose cushions on seating and back. The tufted cushions give the long and straight design a bit more tension, yet the sofa keeps its powerful appearance. The rosewood frame is additionally reinforced by the double connections. In this the grain of the rosewood is beautifully visible.

We advise reupholstery as the original fabric shows signs of age and use, as well as the stuffing of the cushions. Please ask for more information about the options that our upholstery studio can offer you.

items.title: Saporiti Sofa in Golden Yellow Reupholstered Velvet and Rosewood
items.description:
Saporiti sofa, rosewood and yellow fabric, Italy, 1960s.

This sofa, equipped with a solid rosewood frame is reupholstered in high quality yellow velours like fabric. Done by our own team of specialists of our in-house atelier. The sofa is designed in order to give it that very distinguished long and low look. Loose cushions on seating and back. The tufted cushions give the long and straight design a bit more tension, yet the sofa keeps its powerful appearance. The rosewood frame is additionally reinforced by the double connections. In this the grain of the rosewood is beautifully visible.

items.title: Saporiti Four-Seat Sofa in Green Velvet and Rosewood
items.description:
Saporiti, four-seat sofa, green velvet and rosewood, Italy, 1960s. 

The sofa is designed in order to give it that very distinguished long and low look. Loose cushions on seating and back. The tufted cushions give the long and straight design a bit more tension, yet the sofa keeps its powerful appearance. The rosewood frame is additionally reinforced by the double connections. In this the grain of the rosewood is visible beautifully.

Please keep in mind that fabric of this piece is original and that we advice reupholstery as the foam needs to be replaced too. Ask one of our advisors for more information.

items.title: Saporiti Lounge Chairs in Green Velvet and Rosewood
items.description:
Saporiti, set of two lounge chairs in rosewood and green velvet fabric, Italy, 1960s.

These chairs, equipped with a rosewood frame still hold their original green upholstery. These chairs are designed in a modest, yet distinguished look. The chairs feature a balanced aesthetic thanks to the combination of the warm vibrant yellow velvet and the warm, natural rosewood frame. The chairs have high armrests that slope only slightly downwards towards the edge. The chairs are designed as a shell to embrace the sitter so these chairs are comfortable and elegant. Interesting details can be seen in the legs that feature architectural almost Art Deco inspired features.

We advise reupholstery as the original fabric shows signs of age and use, especially on the armrests. The experienced craftsman of our in-house atelier are specialist on reupholstery of design furniture. With high attention for the original, they make sure every piece retains it's value and is ready for the many years to come.

items.title: Rare Alexander Girard for Herman Miller Sofa and Chair, All Original
items.description:
These furniture designs by Alexander Girard were only produced in 1967-1968. Very few exist today and even fewer in this condition. This set is completely original and in extremely fine condition. The set features Girard's Checker upholstery and are signed with applied disc manufacturer's label to underside: [Herman Miller Inc. Zeeland, Mich.].

Literature: Alexander Girard Designs for Herman Miller, Piña, ppg. 130-133, 134.

Sofa dimensions: See below.
Armchair dimensions: 40 W x 28 D x 26 H inches.

items.title: Customizable Mario Bellini 'Camaleonda' Modular Sofa in Cognac Leather
items.description:
Mario Bellini, large modular 'Cameleonda' sofa, cognac leather upholstery, Italy, 1971, reupholstered by our in-house upholstery atelier. 

The sectional elements this sofa was made with can be used freely and apart from one another. This sofa is part of our customized midcentury collection. The backs and armrests are provided with rings and carabiners, which allows the user to create a perfect 'seating landscape.' This design became famous almost immediately after it was featured in the exhibition 'The New Domestic Landscape' held in the MOMA Museum in 1972. The sofa is very comfortable, and the fact this wonderful piece is modular, provides endless flexible solutions for any project or living room. This sofa consists out of seven seating elements, five large elements and two smaller ones. In addition of five backrests and two armrests. The sofa was completely reupholstered in a wonderful cognac leather by the experienced craftsmen of our in-house atelier.

Mario Bellini (1935-) is trained as an architect and became one of the leading designers in post-war Italian style. In the beginning of his career, he worked together with Olivetti and Cassina which resulted in an early knowledge of synthetic resins and polyurethanes. His furniture is exciting, both in its use of material as in the originality of his designs. Bellini did not believe in precise boundaries of design, instead, he designed for the relationship of man and environment. It is impossible to pigeon hole Bellini's oeuvre, as his work is so complex and original.

Measurements are per large element.

Literature:

- Ambasz, Emilio. Italy: The New Domestic Landscape. Achievements and Problems of Italian Design. New York: MoMA, 1972.
- Gramigna, Giuliana. Repertorio del Design Italiano 1950-2000 per L'Arredamento Domestico. Allemandi: Torino, 2003, p. 188.

items.title: Ib Kofod-Larsen 'Elizabeth' Chair in Original Cognac Leather with Ottoman
items.description:
Ib Kofod-Larsen for Christensen & Larsen, model U-56 'Elizabeth' with ottoman, in teak and cognac leather, Denmark, 1956. 

This is Kofod-Larsen's highest-quality armchair with ottoman, with a teak frame and beautiful details in the design. The leather holds beautiful original leather with authentic patina. The carved teak frame runs all the way from the front pointy front via the legs to the rear. Upholstered in cognac leather, with a very comfortable loose cushion. Produced by Christensen & Larsen in 1956 and since it was purchased by Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip during their visit to Copenhagen in 1958, it is called the “Elizabeth Chair.” 

Measurements ottoman: 
D 46 x W 56.5 x H 36.5 cm.

items.title: Customizable Mario Bellini 'Camaleonda' Sofa in Tri-Tone Velvet
items.description:
Mario Bellini, 'Camaleonda' sofa, in orange upholstery by Italy, 1972.

This sofa is part of our customized midcentury design collection, made on request in our upholstery atelier. The sectional elements this sofa was made with, can be used freely and apart from one another. The backs and armrests are provided with rings and carabiners, which allows the user to create a perfect 'seating landscape.' The sofa is very comfortable and the fact this wonderful piece is modular, provides endless flexible solutions for any project or living room. This design became famous almost immediately after it was featured in the exhibition 'Italy and The New Domestic Landscape' in the MOMA Museum in 1972.

Mario Bellini (1935-) is trained as an architect and became one of the leading designers in postwar Italian style. In the beginning of his career, he worked together with Olivetti and Cassina which resulted in an early knowledge of synthetic resins and polyurethanes. His furniture is exciting, both in its use of material as in the originality of his designs. Bellini did not believe in precise boundaries of design, instead, he designed for the relationship of man and environment. It is impossible to pigeon hole Bellini's oeuvre, as his work is so complex and original.

This sectional sofa will be upholstered on special request. Please note a complete sofa has a lead time of 5 to 6 weeks, all to meet our high standards. 

Literature: 
- Gramigna, Giuliana. Repertorio del Design Italiano 1950-2000 per L'Arredamento Domestico. Allemandi: Torino, 2003, p. 188.
- Morteo, Enrico. Mario Bellini. Furniture, Machines & Objects. London: Phaidon, 2008, p. 94.
- Ambasz, Emilio. Italy: The New Domestic Landscape. Achievements and Problems of Italian Design. New York: MoMA, 1972, p. 120.

items.title: Federico Munari, Sofa Curvato in Velvet Mohair and Brass, Italy, circa 1950
items.description:
Attributed to Federico Munari
Curvato sofa
Velvet mohair ("Teddy" fabric from Maison Pierre Frey), Brass
Italy, circa 1950

Measures: H 90 x L 270 x P 100 cm.

items.title: Gio Ponti, Curved Four-Seat Sofa, Beige Velvet, Dark Beech Legs, Italy, 1940s
items.description:
An organically shaped / curved, large four-seat sofa designed by Gio Ponti. Produced by Casa e Giardino in the 1940s. Reupholstered in a high quality beige velvet fabric. Legs in original dark stained beech. This early modernist work has the scale and comfort of a contemporary luxury sofa.

Comes with a "Certificate of Authenticity" from the Gio Ponti Archives.

Gio Ponti is arguably the most famous Italian architects and modern designer of all time. Among many ventures he co-founded Fontana Arte in partnership with Pietro Chiesa. He occasionally designed pieces in partnership with Piero Fornasetti other designers of the era include Carlo Mollino, Isamu Noguchi. Jean Royere, Ico Parisi and Carlo Di Carli.

items.title: La Gondola Sofa in Gray Mohair by Edward Wormley for Dunbar
items.description: Monumental 10' La Gondola sofa by Edward Wormley for Dunbar. Fully restored. Refinished mahogany base in walnut finish with brass hardware. Newly upholstered in smoke gray mohair.

items.title: Ubald Klug Set of Four Patinated 'Landscapes' by De Sede
items.description:
Ubald Klug for De Sede, four DS1025 'Terrazza' landscape elements, in white high quality leather, by Switzerland, 1970s. 

This waterfall shaped sofa in white to grey leather by the Swiss manufacturer De Sede is part of our midcentury design collection. The design for this sofa was inspired by natural phenomena such as rock formations or waves. The sofas can be compared to terraced hills with widths and depths that vary in tapering steps. Both playful and opulent; the design of this landscape is simply spectacular. 

De Sede once started as a saddler's workshop in Klingnau, Switzerland. Slowly, the company widened their Scope and committed themselves to transforming the best possible leather into seating furniture. In 1965 the family-run business grew into a professional company and their name was De Sede AG. DeSede products are detail-obsessed with the main focus on the people who own and use them. Therefore, all the De Sede items are made out of the best materials which results in durability and comfort.

items.title: Poul Kjærholm PK-31/3 Sofa by E. Kold Christensen in Denmark
items.description: Rare PK-31/3 sofa in cognac brown leather with amazing patina and flat steel designed by Poul Kjærholm. Produced by first producer E. Kold Christensen in Denmark. Designed in 1958.

items.title: Extreme Wood Sofa in Solid Walnut Wood and Genuine Grey Leather
items.description:
Sofa extreme wood with structure in hand-carved, hand-polished,
hand-patinated solid walnut wood. Subtle wood work upholstered
with seat and back with high quality genuine grey leather. 
Also available with structure in oak or cherry or maple or elm solid
wood with high quality genuine grey leather or other finishes on request.
Exceptional piece.

items.title: Gio Ponti Sofa by ISA, circa 1950
items.description:
Important large sofa designed by Gio Ponti and produced by ISA Bergamo during the 1950s. Labelled and numbered. The sofa has been left as found. It needs to be re-upholstered.
Prod. I.S.A., Italia, circa 1950.

items.title: Renzo Zavanella, Important Sofa from Hotel San Remo, Light Fabric, Walnut, 1950
items.description:
An organic sofa made for hotel San Remo (Rome, Italy), circa 1950, by Italian designer Renzo Zavanella. The design most likely conceived in the latter half of the, 1940s. 

The lively overstuffed form with two high backs provides excellent comfort. Mounted on exquisite organically formed walnut legs. 

The form has an organic expression similar to works by artists of the same era in Italy, such as Carlo Mollino , Campo Graffi, Ico Parisi and Gio Ponti.

Literature: Stilnovo Design in den 50er Jahren, Borngraber, pg. 13Les Annees 50, Bony, pg. 186.

result.aboutUs:
At Morentz (est. 2007), we aim to add value to every single piece in our collection. We are a gallery, a workshop and an upholstery studio in one. Our team consists of about forty restorators, upholsterers, interior advisors and art historians. We are therefore able to provide our customer with every possible service. 

Every day, securely selected twentieth century design arrives at our warehouse from every corner of the world. We investigate every single edge and every inch of patina. We check the structure and condition thoroughly. This is where we add our value: what does a piece need? It might be a careful and complete restoration or a completely new upholstery, depending on each individual piece and each individual client. Our aim is to stay true to the original intention of the designer and at the same time fulfill the wishes of its new owner. At Morentz, nothing is impossible, because we love and care about our pieces as much as you do.
